{
  "text": "The bound and unbound CO 2 concentrations depend on the partial pressure of carbon dioxide P CO 2 , percent oxygen saturation S O 2 , hematocrit Hct, gas solubility a CO 2 , temperature T and pH [CITATION_1] (see Blood carbon dioxide in Appendix). Also similar to the treatment of oxygen is the need for an effective solubility\u00e3",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "29238493"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "29238493": {
      "title": "Digital computer procedure for the conversion of PCO2 into blood CO2 content",
      "abstract": "A digital computer procedure for the conversion of carbon dioxide tension into whole blood CO2 content at various temperatures and in the presence of metabolic acidosis or alkalosis is described. The CO2 content of the plasma is calculated from the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation (allowing for the dependence of pK and CO2 solubility in plasma on temperature and pH); and the CO2 content of the blood is then determined using an empirical approximation of the ratio [CO2] cells: [CO2] plasma based on the experimental data of Van Slyke and Sendroy. This computer procedure is self-contained and is ready for inclusion in larger programs without modification."
    }
  }
}